    <title>the new math, 1965</title>
    <content type='html'>&lt;div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"&gt;
&lt;a href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhLkbi7oWYU5V7eBZ5DeL7z1UKLDyW750pNtAVxlnzKs1Zqlzbm1ul2sPxCCE3OpmeKg8OA8iVRPp8tVuAAcfmYdfdouW8y5g_KF0WkF5Z1c37KPM4me0WYW8-f4GllQHi8tCqyaNavT8o/s1600/cbc_logo.jpg" imageanchor="1" style="margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;"&gt;&lt;img border="0" height="200" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhLkbi7oWYU5V7eBZ5DeL7z1UKLDyW750pNtAVxlnzKs1Zqlzbm1ul2sPxCCE3OpmeKg8OA8iVRPp8tVuAAcfmYdfdouW8y5g_KF0WkF5Z1c37KPM4me0WYW8-f4GllQHi8tCqyaNavT8o/s200/cbc_logo.jpg" width="200" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The clip below (you can find it &lt;a href="http://archives.cbc.ca/society/education/clips/15140/"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; if it doesn't display) about &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Math"&gt;the new math&lt;/a&gt; is from an 1965 broadcast of the CBC television program &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/This_Hour_Has_Seven_Days"&gt;This Hour has Seven Days&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
At the end of the segment, the studio audience provided generally balanced and thoughtful responses to the rather slanted questions posed by &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurier_LaPierre"&gt;Laurier LaPierre&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;- they voiced the concerns and issues that are perpetual companions of public education, and that we still hear today.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
If you are wondering about the references to "the parachute man" at the beginning of the clip, you can see just about the full program &lt;a href="http://ms.radio-canada.ca/archives_new/2007/en/wmv/seven_days_19650110.wmv"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; (or you can find it as clip #4 on &lt;a href="http://archives.cbc.ca/programs/754/"&gt;this page&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;br /&gt;
